<BaseLayout
  title="About Godspeed You! Black Emperor / gybe.org"
  description="Background on Godspeed You! Black Emperor, the band's name, early cassette history, and the source-minded archive approach behind gybe.org."
>
  <h1 class="page-title">about</h1>
  <p class="deck">
    Godspeed You! Black Emperor is a Montreal collective whose music moves through long-form instrumental rock, field recordings, tape loops, political dread, and fragile release.
  </p>

  <section class="content">
    <h2>about GY!BE</h2>
    <p>
      Godspeed You! Black Emperor formed in Montreal in 1994 around Efrim Menuck, Mike Moya, and Mauro Pezzente. What began as a small local project expanded into a large, shifting ensemble of guitars, basses, drums, strings, tape loops, field recordings, and film projections.
    </p>
    <p>
      The band became one of the defining names in long-form instrumental rock without adopting the usual machinery of rock publicity. Their records tend to work through accumulation: fragments of speech, slow harmonic movement, patient repetition, sudden mass, and moments where dread and hope occupy the same space.
    </p>

    <h2>the name</h2>
    <p>
      The name comes from Mitsuo Yanagimachi's 1976 Japanese documentary <em>God Speed You! Black Emperor</em>, a black-and-white film about a Bosozoku motorcycle gang. The archive keeps that origin in view because the name is not just branding: it connects the band to images of youth, speed, alienation, hierarchy, and social pressure.
    </p>
    <p>
      The band has used several written forms of its name over time, including Godspeed You Black Emperor! and Godspeed You! Black Emperor. This site uses Godspeed You! Black Emperor as the main modern form and GY!BE as the common abbreviation.
    </p>

    <h2>the first album</h2>
    <p>
      The earliest release, <em>All Lights Fucked on the Hairy Amp Drooling</em>, was a tiny 1994 cassette edition that became a long-running fan mystery. It is not the sound most listeners associate with the later band, but it matters because it documents the project before the large ensemble language had formed.
    </p>
    <p>
      For years the cassette was discussed more as legend than as a widely heard record. In 2022, after the material surfaced online, the band officially released it through Bandcamp and confirmed its authenticity.
    </p>

    <h2>archive approach</h2>
    <p>
      gybe.org is an unofficial fan archive. It points outward to official sources for records, live dates, tickets, and label information. It does not host lyrics, and it avoids presenting uncertain fan lore as fact.
    </p>
  </section>
